commits.message:
Replace git-checkout with git-switch in guides

The functionality of git-checkout was split into git-switch and
git-restore in version 2.23 (2019-08) in order to be (slightly) less
confusing. The checkout command won't go away soon, but switch will
likely be easier for new users to remember.
commits.author: Eamon

commits.message:
Fix tests running at 23:59pm UTC

Here's a fun one. Because the `Date.current` is evaluated as the file
loads, if the test suite starts up at 23:59pm, any tests that run in
the minute thereafter will be using the improper validation.

By using a proc to load the date range, this can be avoided (so the
validation will use the range accurate as of whenever the validation is
running).

I'm not sure whether this was a bug in production or not. I'd think we
would have heard of it if it were...?
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Make Argyle::EventsController tests verify WebhookEvent creation

These tests previously seemed to verify WebhookEvent creation, but due
to a test setup problem, they were actually only asserting that an "ok"
response was returned. Since the `argyle_user_id` was not matching a
valid CBV flow, the WebhookEvent was not being created.

commits.message:
corrected sending client_agency_id to the event logger in many places, also a few locale updates (#541)

Corrected an issue Eryn noticed during acceptance testing: not all new events were properly getting the client_agency_id or locale attributes set. I fixed this for the new events and re-tested many of the existing ones.

There are a few events directly from pinwheel that still don't get these 100% correctly, but I think that's acceptable since so many other events do; it will be easy to determine what the values for these attributes likely were if they're missing, since they'll be on a user with many other events with these attributes set correctly.
commits.author: Tim Miller

commits.message:
Fix ThrottlingError when running migrations (#497)

We've been getting a ThrottlingError when running migrations a few times
(see [1], [2], [3]).

It's because the `--query` argument is evaluated client-side after
receiving the full list from the server, and therefore the
`describe-log-streams` call is paginating through all 174 pages of our
8300+ log streams just to select the single one we're looking for.
Github Actions' internet connection seems to be fast enough to hit the
[25 requests/second rate limit][4].

Let's use the `--log-stream-name-prefix` option instead to filter it
server-side. We can still use a (simpler) `--query` to count the
results client-side.

[1]: https://github.com/DSACMS/iv-cbv-payroll/actions/runs/13775537056/job/38524000928
[2]: https://github.com/DSACMS/iv-cbv-payroll/actions/runs/13730036473/job/38405238446
[3]: https://github.com/DSACMS/iv-cbv-payroll/actions/runs/13727774147/job/38398210761
[4]: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatchLogs/latest/APIReference/API_DescribeLogStreams.html
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
FFS-2340: Encapsulate Events Handling in a New Model (#491)

We currently use Pinwheel-specific columns on `PayrollAccount` to track
the status of the sync: income/paystubs/employment/identity
synced_at/errored_at.

To accommodate other payroll aggregators, and better record sync
statuses, let's create a WebhookEvents model to record which webhooks
we've received for a given PayrollAccount. Success or failure, then, is
not determined by the columns, but by the presence of the necessary
WebhookEvents for that payroll aggregator.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Fix flaky rake tests by always loading Rake tasks once (#439)

If `Rails.application.load_tasks` is called multiple times, than any
invocation of a Rake task will actually happen multiple times. This is
problematic for non-idempotent Rake tasks (like
`users:promote_to_service_account`).

Let's prevent this issue by just loading the tasks in the
"rails_helper.rb" file so they're always available.

commits.message:
Track eight events from Pinwheel modal interactions

These events cover most of what we're hoping to instrument for future
Pinwheel sessions. In the order a user may experience them:

1. `PinwheelShowProviderConfirmationPage` - sent when a provider
   confirmation screen is shown (e.g. "Amazon" showing multiple
   platforms like A to Z and ADP)
2. `PinwheelShowLoginPage` - sent when the first screen of a login is
   shown (whether it's employer disambiguation, username/password, or
   other input required by user)
3. `PinwheelAttemptLogin` - sent when the user attempts login (sent only
   once on the first screen even if there are subsequent screens for MFA
   or other employer-specific questions). Unfortunately, there are no
   Pinwheel events on the subsequent login pages.
4. `PinwheelError` - sent when an error occurs, likely an incorrect
   login or MFA code, but also a system error.
5. `PinwheelSuccess` - sent when the login completes.

If the user doesn't follow the intended path through the modal, they may
trigger:
6. `PinwheelShowDefaultProviderSearch` - sent when the user deselects
   the employer or platform and returns to the beginning of the pinwheel
   modal
7. `PinwheelAttemptClose` - shown when the user clicks the "X" in the
   modal, before confirming the closure
8. `PinwheelCloseModal` - shown when the modal actually closes
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Refactor "user action" tracking on employer search page

* Make the /api/pinwheel/user_action endpoint generic so it can receive
  an "eventName" and arbitrary "attributes" for an event. This will be
  used in subsequent commits for Pinwheel modal events.
* Create new event, `ApplicantSelectedEmployerOrPlatformItem`, to
  replace events `ApplicantSelectedPopularPayrollPlatform` and
  `ApplicantSelectedPopularAppEmployer`. A unified event prevents the
  javascript from having to know which event to send, and will also make
  funnel analysis and future maintenance easier.
* Add an attribute `is_default_option` to the new event so we can tell
  apart clicks on the 12 default items from clicks on search results.
* Add the `name` attribute to also be present on search results (as it
  was previously only present on the default options)
* Add tests for user action API
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Fix data redaction for Cbv Flows without invitations (#334)

We have a number of these in the database from early in the application:
Cbv Flows that didn't originate from an invitation. Currently, the data
redaction is failing for these records because we use the invitation's
expiration date as the threshold for when to redact the data.

We'll need to handle this situation properly given we're planning to
allow invitation-less CBV for real in the near-future, so let's update
the logic here so we redact Cbv Flows based on either:
* The invitation's expriation + 7 days (if invited)
* The Cbv Flow's most recent update + 7 days (if not invited)

By using the update timestamp, we can try our best to not redact an
active Cbv Flow that someone is actively completing (i.e. if they
started the flow and then kept their browser active for 7 days).
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
1646: Invalidate sessions on logout (addresses MA security finding)

This may be too clever to last long-term, but, to prevent against reuse
of session after logout, this commit adds logic to maintain a JSON
object of invalidated session IDs in the `users` table.

When logging out, the session ID is stored in that JSON object. If the
user attempts to reuse the old session, we will not accept the login.

This also enforces server-side session timeouts of 30 minutes, to
prevent re-use of old sessions.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Fix MA GPG encryption in production

In production (only), our docker containers are read-only, which
prevents the GPG key from being added to the local keyring.

We should probably redo this at build-time, but until then, let's tell
GPG to create our keyring in the writable directory.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

subscribing our personal email addresses to it. (Again, only for
debugging purposes until we have actual real data.)

commits.message:
1577: Fix error that happens during PDF rendering

The issue was that, when precompiling assets during the Docker build,
the DOMAIN_NAME environment variable is not set, leading to incomplete
URLs being referenced by the stylesheets built by the asset pipeline,
for example:

  background-image: url(https:/assets/@uswds/uswds/dist/img/file[...].svg)

Since the same asset build is used for both demo and production, we
can't have a domain name in there. So, let's unset the
`config.asset_host`, so that no domain name is included during
compilation, and instead set the fine-grained
`config.action_mailer.action_host`, which is only used in the mailers.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Revert "Use "Strict" Set-Cookie SameSite value"

This reverts commit 5b788c91a1a1fb8192d805d017cf117284f8dd64.

Reading the definition of "SameSite=Strict" a bit closer, it says

> If a request originates from a different domain or scheme (even with
> the same domain), no cookies with the SameSite=Strict attribute are
> sent.

This was breaking SSO because the session cookie wasn't being sent to
the OmniAuth callbacks controller, since the navigation request
originates from a different domain (Microsoft's SSO page).

We don't actually need Set-Cookie=Strict for security reasons, it's only
a nice-to-have.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Set Cache-Control and X-Content-Type-Options headers on static assets

The former is a performance optimization. The latter will quell a
security alert.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Remove `secure_headers` gem

Ironically, this gem is making our headers less secure and worse.
Without the gem, Rails by default will:

* Set a `Referrer-Policy: same-origin-when-cross-origin` header, which
  is a good best-practice.
* Set `X-XSS-Protection: 0`, which reflects the reality that [all
  browsers have removed support for it][1]

I've also removed the `new_framework_defaults_7_0.rb` as we are already
loading the 7.0 defaults, so everything in that file is already being
included by Rails by default.

[1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/X-XSS-Protection
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Use "Strict" Set-Cookie SameSite value

[This MDN page][1] describes the "Strict" SameSite value as:

> Means that the browser sends the cookie only for same-site requests,
> that is, requests originating from the same site that set the cookie. If
> a request originates from a different domain or scheme (even with the
> same domain), no cookies with the SameSite=Strict attribute are sent.

Since all our requests should be on the same site, we can set this to
Strict so that it's one less thing the security scanners will nag us
about.

[1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Set-Cookie#samesitesamesite-value
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Redirect to homepage after timed out employer search

If the session times out right before the user searches for an employer,
the homepage redirect will be handled by turbo, which is expecting to
find a <turbo-frame id="employers"> in the response. Since the homepage
doesn't have such a frame, it displays a "Content missing" error message
and the user is stuck.

We need to catch the failure event for this page and force a top-level
page redirect.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Expire session cookies after 30 minutes of inactivity

Finishes FFS-1294. This commit tweaks the session logic by:
1. Configuring Rails to set the `Expires-In` cookie header, so browsers
   will automatically stop sending the cookie. In this case, the user
   will be redirected to the homepage with a message telling them to go
   back and click the link again.
2. If the user clicks the invitation link again, they will resume from
   the /entry page if they haven't connected any Pinwheel accounts, or,
   if they have, they will resume from the payment details page of the
   most recently-connected account.

commits.message:
Fix downloading PDF after completing CBV flow

It was broken because it was mistakenly redirecting to the expired
tokens URL. This commit tweaks how we do session management like so:

1. If the user hits the "Back" button after reaching the "success" page
   (or goes to any other /cbv/ url), they will be redirected back to the
   success page, with the CbvFlow still in their session (so the page
   can render). This will create consistency so people don't
   accidentally get locked out of their session after it's complete. We
   will rely on session expiration (coming in the future) so that
   reopening the browser after a long time does not return the user to
   the success page.
2. That makes the "expired" page only used when *starting* a new flow
   from a token.
3. After those changes, we can just skip the completeness check when
   downloading the PDF to ensure that it is always possible.

commits.message:
Fix CSP to allow inline styles

The `style-src` directive blocks both elements (`<style>` and `<link
rel="stylesheet">`) as well as attributes (`<div style="...">`). The
directive can be split into two, which is necessary for us in order for
our inline styles on the payment_details page (and elsewhere) to render
properly.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Fix employer search inadvertently using CSP

The Pinwheel employer search will not work when a CSP is in effect,
since Pinwheel uses inline <style> tags. The CSP is disabled in the
controller, however, when the employer search page is requested via
Hotwire/Turbo, the headers that disable CSP don't apply to the root html
document.

So, disabling turbo on the previous page form will do the trick -
forcing the browser to do a full load of the next page with the proper
CSP.

commits.message:
Move Pinwheel API token into site-config.yml

This will allow us to have sites using different Pinwheel
configurations. The intent here is that we will be able to have a
"sandbox" site that is always using the Pinwheel sandbox while we can
have NYC and MA in the Pinwheel "development" environment so they can
access real data.

This necessitates always having a "site_id" present when instantiating a
PinwheelService object, so that it can pull the correct API token from
the site configuration. Every place we do it except one, we have access
to a `cbv_flow` object, so it works. (The exception is the dev webhooks
manager, which I updated to only create webhooks for the "sandbox"
site.)

There is one gotcha in the Pinwheel webhook events controller: we
previously validated the webhook signature *before* loading the CbvFlow
model (good!) However, now we need to load the CbvFlow object first in
order to have the API token to use to validate the webhook signature. To
prevent timing attacks that would allow enumeration of the
`pinwheel_end_user_id` field, if the CbvFlow object is not found, we
still pretend to validate the webhook signature using a dummy API token
so it takes approximately the same duration.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Fix demo deploys by pulling image from correct account_id

Deploys to our demo (dev) environment were broken because they were
trying to pull the built image from the wrong AWS account (dev instead
of prod). This is because the service module was using a
"data.aws_ecr_repository" module to load the repository by name, despite
the fact that the ECR repository was in another account.

The fix for this is to pass in the "image_repository_account_id" to the
service module. We determine the value when processing the app-config by
calling the bin/account-ids-by-name.sh script, and looking for the
account ID for the account that contains the "shared" environment.

This commit also updates the publish-release.sh script. Although this
script worked (as the Github Action properly ran it in the shared
environment), I thought it would be good to standardize how the image
repository values were accessed.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Fix production deploy by pushing built images to prod registry

Production deploys are currently failing due to the task not being able
to [pull the built image from the registry][1]. Upon further inspection,
this is probably because there is a mismatch between the configuration
for the "shared" AWS environment (which points to the "nava-ffs" dev
account and will be used by GH Actions when [building and pushing the
image][2]) and the actual [configuration of the "shared" Terraform
backend][3] (which points to the production account).

This commit harmonizes these environments in a hope that it just works.
I can't test this, since it's Github Actions, so I'm going to rely on
merging and seeing how it goes after that.

I also removed "staging" config for now, since we don't intend to have a
staging environment right now. I've left it commented-out so we can
quickly retrieve it if we see the need for it later.

[1]: https://github.com/DSACMS/iv-cbv-payroll/actions/runs/10171383905/job/28134142130
[2]: https://github.com/DSACMS/iv-cbv-payroll/blob/82a4f2b2/.github/workflows/build-and-publish.yml#L45-L52
[3]: https://github.com/DSACMS/iv-cbv-payroll/blob/82a4f2b2/infra/app/build-repository/shared.s3.tfbackend

commits.message:
Update task_executor IAM policy before running migrations

When adding an environment variable to AWS SSM, the task executor will
need access to read the environment variable in order to start up a
container. This is normally handled later in the deploy, when the
`bin/deploy-release.sh` script runs `make infra-update-app-service`. But
by then, the migrations container will already have failed.

This commit updates the targets for the pre-migration `terraform` run to
also update the `aws_iam_role_policy.task_executor` resource so that it
will have the permissions it needs to start up the migrations.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

Update PinwheelWebhookManager to not recreate the same webhook

When the Rails server is reloading, the Pinwheel webhook will be the

commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Fix PinwheelService to hide unsupported employers from search

When searching, we attempt to restrict search results to only those with
"paystubs" listed as a "job" that Pinwheel can perform for us. If
Pinwheel doesn't support the "paystubs" job, we can't get the data we
need for the product to actually work.

Some employers were breaking when clicking the "Select" button: these
employers didn't support the Pinwheel "paystubs" job, and we weren't
filtering them out of the results correctly due to a bug.

The issue here is that we were encoding the API request parameters
incorrectly, as:

  POST /v1/search?q=foo&required_jobs[]=paystubs

The correct way to encode the `required_jobs` URL param, per API docs,
is:

  POST /v1/search?q=foo&required_jobs=paystubs

(any additional values in the required_jobs array would be passed as
repeated parameters)

I ran some metrics: 6% of Pinwheel's 2620 employers will be filtered out
as a result. The biggest ones that I saw were USPS, Walgreens, Duane
Reade, and Harris Teeter.

Finishes FFS-952.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
Allow specifying `single_nat_gateway` in network_config

NAT Gateways are pricey, at $32/month, and also entail provisioning
an Elastic IP ($4/month). This isn't going to break the bank, but also,
it isn't necessary at all for our non-production environments since they
can tolerate an unlikely AWS AZ outage.

This commit adds the ability to pass through a `single_nat_gateway`
variable all the way to the `vpc` module, which supports sending all our
external traffic via a single NAT gateway.

* The secret is provided by the "CBV_INVITE_SECRET" environment
  variable. In development, it is "development".
* This controller will send the invitation according to the
  CbvInvitationService (which isn't currently wired up to a real email
  sending feature, but will be!)

Other things this commit does:
* Refactor out the testing method for setting environment variables into
  a globally-accessible TestHelpers module.
* Adds USWDS "Alert" components to the layout for `flash[:notice]` and
  `flash[:alert]` messages, so we can easily add these to other pages as
  well.

Finishes FFS-823.

commits.message:
Remove credentials.yml.enc in favor of env vars (#38)

* Fix rubocop style issues

This commit runs `rubocop --autocorrect` to fix the style issues.

* Remove encrypted credentials file

As this is a public repo, we won't be storing credentials encrypted in
this file. Instead, we will use environment variables.

* Remove cloud.gov Redis configuration

This appeared to be attempting to configure Redis based off an
environment variable called VCAP_SERVICES with some kind of JSON blob of
configuration. This appears to be a Cloud Foundry concept that we aren't
using.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

commits.message:
applying changes from previous infra setup (#31)

* Mount /rails/tmp as temp directory

Puma writes its pid to a temporary pidfile in ./tmp/pids by default,
however, this was a problem because we were mounting the whole
filesystem as readonly.

To allow for creation of this pid file and whatever else Rails needs
that tmp directory for, let's mount it in as an ephemeral volume from
Fargate.

This commit also includes some README changes to reflect my experience
getting terraform and docker running on my laptop.

* updating db prod config to use env vars

* changed file system to read only

* reverting the db reset logic, adding grant privileges to sequences and routines

* removed RESET arg from run-database-migrations.sh, added ARGYLE_SANDBOX

* removed the ARGYLE_SANDBOX from the env secrets

* Add new env variables

commits.message:
Configure ngrok and Argyle webhooks automatically

When starting the development server (using `bin/dev`), this script
configures Ngrok automatically via:

1. Starting ngrok with foreman like the other processes
2. Adding a Rails initializer to auto-detect a running local ngrok
   tunnel
3. If there is a running local tunnel, create an Argyle webhook
   subscription automatically to it
4. Clean up any other Argyle webhook subscriptions that may be left over
   from before (based on the name)

A couple configuration changes were necessary:
* config.hosts needed a wildcard allowance of anything at
  `.ngrok-free.app`, since by the time the initializer runs, it's too
  late to change config.hosts
* Since NGROK_URL isn't available anymore, we'll need a better answer
  for sending email URLs.

commits.message:
Remove OWASP scan on every PR

We may want to bring this back someday. This scanner seems to operate by
making a Github issue with any scan discrepancies. That seems fine to
run daily, but on every PR it may be noisy if it is creating separate
issues for those.

I read through the warnings, and none seemed to be really that
significant. I also downloaded the local ZAP program in hopes of
replicating the warnings, but got an (almost entirely) different set of
warnings back.

For now, until we understand this tool better, I'm inclined to disable
it.
commits.author: Tom Dooner

Move SECRET_KEY_BASE to config/credentials/ci.yml.enc

The `rake db:schema:load` command was failing for lack of this variable.
By moving it to the `config/credentials` YAML file, it will be applied
by default to all commands, rather than just the `rake assets:precompile`
command.

commits.message:
Upgrade GH Actions upload-sarif v1 -> v3

This appears to upload the security scan result to CodeQL. V1 was
EOL'd some time ago, and V2 is going to be EOL at the end of 2024.

The main difference with V3 is that it uses Node 20, but hopefully it
will be compatible with our older Node 18 install.
